Last April, I ran away to Puerto Rico for my 40th birthday in an effort to really soak up the milestone and break free from the non-stop work cycle. I posted something on the big day and then said, “Let me put down Instagram for a few hours and take a break from the grid!” 

It’s been 11 months. Oops! 

The truth is, turning 40 really thew me for a loop. I don’t know about y’all but I remember going to those Hallmark stores as a kid and seeing those cards, balloons, and banners that read “Happy 40th Birthday, OVER THE HILL!” It’s seared into my brain — alongside that cartoon Bea Arthur-looking a-hole Maxine, who’d be like “Welcome to your 40s! I got you a coffin!”

Times have obviously changed since then and our collective attitudes around aging, with it. But that number — 40! — still holds a lot of weight for me. Like that Hallmark propaganda did, it made me highly aware of societal’s timeline; that idea that by a certain age, you SHOULD be doing X, Y, Z. “I SHOULD be married by now. I SHOULD own property. I SHOULD have a family. I SHOULD have health insurance. I SHOULD not be living paycheck to paycheck, stressed constantly about having enough money to pay my rent and feed myself.” You know, life!. 

All I could think of was all the things that passed me by. And while that feeling still creeps in from time to time, I’ve used these past few months to break past that bad habit of SHOULDS. In fact, I’ve all but removed that world from my vocabulary. Instead. I’m focused on COULDS — all those endless possibilities coming — and really reminding myself to walk my own path without these idiotic deadlines. There’s so much I’ve accomplished that was NEVER on that timeline. And so much I’m going to do I never dreamed of. 

Thanks for being there for the ride. Let’s go.

And while we’re catching up, look who came to Puerto Rico too…

Most of you know @constantlygus, my best friend and boyfriend of 4+ years now. Over the past 11 months, Gus has achieved incredible success in his professional life, including a sold-out headlining tour, passing over 120K followers on IG and writing for some killer animated kids shows like Princess Power, Gabby’s Dollhouse and Rugrats! 

(He also had a milestone birthday of his own — turning 30 — though he’s 31 in June so, it may be too late for the Happy Birthdays, I guess). 

Anyway, looking back, I wish I was on IG to celebrate every of Gus’ wins these this year. I’m so beyond proud of him for all that he’s done and all that he is STILL doing. One of the best things about being in a long relationship is you’re there to cheer on the person you’re with as they follow their dreams. How cool is that!?! And the growth I’ve seen from Gus in his career has just been so inspiring. He challenges himself and works tirelessly to go after what he wants, but also knows when to ask for help and support when he needs it. I just admire him so, so much. 

I feel lucky to be in Gus’ orbit, and live in gratitude that we found one another. If you’ve met Gus before, you’ll know, there’s simply no one quite like him around. I get that I’m bias, but he’s the coolest, smartest, funniest, cutest guy I know — with an infectious, charismatic energy and the best smile around. (He’s a good dog dad too, but Cashew can say that in her own post). 

I love the heck out of you, Gus. Thanks for letting me be your teammate and for being mine. I cant wait for a lifetime of vacations like this together.
Mondays, amiright?

Halloween 2022. Cashew went as a Crocodile, I went as Crocodile Dad-dee. It was our first Halloween together, as Cash — though born in September 2021 — hadn’t joined me until that November. Anyway, I had this whole vision of us trick-or-treating through the streets of Park Slope together and people showering us with love, begging for photographs. Instead, we barely made it down the street ‘cause she hated the hood and the tail. So we stopped instead for a stoop photoshoot and called it a day. Next year, we’ll do better!
Also, can this dog model or can this dog model? The RANGE!

A snap from tonight’s #RHONJ, and also from one of my favorite places in the world: MCU Park, home of the Brooklyn Cyclones, in Coney Island. I have so many incredible memories of being there throughout my life, and I love that cheering on the Jersey Housewives are forever a part of that.

This woman right here. Quite frankly, I don’t know a more generous, more caring, more selfless human in the world. So impressed with how she constantly uses her platform for such good — like on tonight’s #RHONJ, where she helped raise over $200,000 for breast cancer research at @maimohealth with her second annual Battle for Brooklyn. I’m so proud to know her, so honored to be in her in orbit, and so grateful for all the good she’s doing in this world. Bravo, @dolorescatania.
One last view. Let’s do it again this summer, @dolorescatania? #RHONJ

Channeling this energy for the rest of the weekend.
Pro tip: If you’re ever lucky enough to be asked, “Hey, do you want to go to Barcelona for 48 hours next week on a last minute press trip?” Say yes — and take lots of pictures!

La Sagrada Familia, easily Barcelona’s No. 1 destination (though the gelato shop I stopped by in Grácia Nova should truly be up there). 

Anyway, construction started on this stunning church on March 19, 1882 and it’s still going on today, with a targeted 2026 completion date. I feel like Hilary Farr from LOVE IT OR LIST IT would have made it happen way faster. She is, as I’ve always said after all, Canada’s Antoni Gaudí. But alas, she’s busy so the construction continues — which, I guess is part of the charm!

Highly recommend getting tickets well in advance so you can see the stunning interiors. It’s apparently even better at sunset if you’re trying to plan, FYI.

Last one to capture my trip to Barcelona. Don’t ask me what the significance of this building is; the tour guide fully explained it but every building there was so beautiful, they all blended in my head. I must have 100 pictures from my trip just like this. In fact, I liked this one so much, I took pictures of it not once, not twice, but THREE times over the course of three separate days without even realizing it. Turns out, I’m a sucker for these innate architectural details and become immediately mesmerized by them — even if they’re just like, housing a Primark or an H&M inside them. Take me back!

I was really feeling down about my birthday this year, and told @constantlygus I didn’t want to do anything but relax. So he surprised me with a trip to the Brooklyn Botanical Gardens, where he told me, “the only thing we have to do here all day is walk around, look at the plants, and take deep breaths.” What a dream! He knows me so well.
41. Or as I’m calling it, “39!”
Thank you for all the lovely birthday messages. I’m so, so grateful for all the kindness and support you’ve shown me. Means more than I’ll ever be able to verbalize.

I’m now a PAPERBACK writer!

That’s right, my book — NOT ALL DIAMONDS AND ROSÉ: THE INSIDE STORY OF THE REAL HOUSEWIVES FROM THE PEOPLE WHO LIVED IT — came out in paperback this week! Available wherever books are sold, it’s still got all the tea and juicy scoops you want, with the flexibility you need to throw it in a beach bag. 

Makes a great Mothers Day gift, birthday gift, or just gift to yourself, dammit! A must for any Housewives fan, if I do say so myself. 💁🏻‍♂️

Clock that new cover for the paperback, y’all! The New York Times No. 1 Bestseller! 

When I started this project, I never believed this book would become as successful as it did, but boy, did y’all prove me wrong! 

I’m so grateful for all the support you’ve shown me since it first came out, and all the kind words you’ve sent my way about this new release. It means the world to me. ❤️

This book really wouldn’t have been possible if it weren’t for the Housewives themselves. This, after all, is their story! And though I’ve said it before, I have to thank again every star who participated in the book, all of whom have been so enthusiastically supportive of it since it came out. Some showed up to the premiere party, others had me on their podcasts — and many posted about it on social media. Why just the other day, I was on the phone with Lisa Vanderpump who was going crazy over it! Still pinching myself that I got to talk to so many of these QUEENS for this project and built such bonds with them. How lucky am I?

NOT ALL DIAMONDS AND ROSÉ — the paperback version — is available now wherever books are sold.
Life is too short not to enjoy every goddamn second of it with the people in your life who you love the most. [📷 @mrdennish]

When your best friend who you’ve known since you were 14 has a birthday and says to you, “Hey, do you want to do something nostalgic on Tuesday to celebrate and go back to Adventureland in Long Island for the first time in 30 years?” — let me tell you, you say yes.

So as July winds down, I figured I’d share some pics from the delightfully fun outing back on July 11. It was so cool to return there for the first time in decades, even if just for an afternoon, with my favorite human on the planet. 

I hope all of you out there have a friend soulmate like Dot; someone who has known you for so long, they can easily clock you for all the humiliating things you used to wear and do; who knows you better than you know yourself; who’s seen you grow and change and supported you at every turn; who you  can talk on the phone with for two hours and STILL hang up leaving more to say; who makes you laugh harder than you’ve laughed before; who always has the best advice to give, even if it’s just, “Do you want to hit the streets and talk smack?”; and who still quotes all your favorite movies to you.

She’s simply the greatest friend, greatest mother, and greatest person I know. Here’s to many more years of nonsense together. 

And remember: I’m the Mary, and you’re the Rhoda.

[📷 @mrdennish]

Also, if you’re going to an amusement park this summer and you think to yourself, “Hey, let’s do the swinging pirate ship ride!” — I’m here to tell you to absolutely NOT do that, especially after you’ve eaten a whole pizza, fries, dippin’ dots, and gone through six water bottle refills (one of which you put Coke Zero in). 

Yes, I’m 41 and nearly hurled all over. And yes, it was my dumb idea to go on the ride in the first place. “Just one more ride, Gus! It’ll be fun!” 🤦🏻‍♂️

"The only time that I look back is to see how far I've come." — Cynthia Bailey

I marked 11 years sober yesterday. 

Typically, this is a day of great celebration for me but this year, it comes at a time of immense change and uncertainty in my life, which is making it harder for me to feel any sense of excitement about anything. 

But I’ve also been practicing radical honesty for the past two months, trying to break a horrible habit of telling white lies when I’m scared of disappointing people. So I might as well apply it here. 

I was raised in an emotionally abusive household in which I was told (both directly and indirectly) that who I am is something to be ashamed of and shown that if I did anything wrong, then I’m unworthy of any love or happiness. I internalized those feelings so deeply that even today, at 41, I return to that baseline. It’s what drove me to drink, what drove me to my suicide attempt that time ago, and what drove me into years of deep, deep depression. 

Every time I’ve tried to get past that, to break that emotional bad habit and reframe my thinking, I’ve been unable to. I’ll get to a place of confidence and self-love and then something will happen and BOOM — I’m right back to being that kid again, re-triggered and starting at the bottom of the mountain. “No one will ever love you.” “You’re a terrible person.” “The world would be a better place without you.” 

But if I’m going to stop lying to other people then I need to stop lying to myself. 

The truth is, I’m a kind, loyal, compassionate person with a sensitive soul who cares deeply about the people in his life and will selflessly do anything for them. I love unconditionally. I celebrate the successes of others. I’m someone who values community, acts of service, laughter, hard work, and cuddle time on the couch. Oh, and TV; lots and lots of TV. 

For the past 11 years, I’ve woken up every day and I’ve chosen myself by choosing not to drink. It hasn’t always been easy, but I’m a person who is clearly capable of self-discovery and self-growth. I’m proud of myself. And I need to remember — if I can do that, I can do anything. 

I heard this phrase from a friend: “God’s a shitty gift wrapper.” Well, she sure is — but boy, am I grateful for the gifts she’s given me.

I don’t think I’ll ever get used to it. A week ago, I was on stage in Las Vegas, moderating a panel at BravoCon for the third year in a row. And when I look at these pictures from the day, it just feels so, so surreal to me — almost as if I’m looking at another person. Damn if I don’t feel like the luckiest guy in the world to be able to live this life. Believe me when I say, I count my blessings every day and moments like these are never taken for granted. Forever grateful. #BravoCon2023

Any moderator will tell you, a successful panel only happens when you have good people on it and I was blessed at BravoCon this year to work with four of the best Housewives around: @jenniferaydin, @lisabarlow14, @kenya, and @garcelle (plus four incredible superfans, including @dakotawright). Thank you all for making “Who Said That Anyway?” such a breeze. I had a blast! See ya next year? #BravoCon2023

At the end of my panel, I made sure to shout out everyone who helped put #BravoCon2023 together and I wanted to continue that gratitude here. The logistics of pulling something like this off are unreal, and every year I’m so amazed at what the team from NBCUniversal and beyond have created. So many hands went into making sure everything looked good and ran smoothly for fans and talent alike, and they all deserve their flowers. From the biggest moments — like the MainStage panels, the rolling live stage, and the nightly ‘BeavoCon Live with Andy Cohen’ episodes — to the “smaller” elements like the signage, lighting, video content, graphics, merch, and vendor booths — everything was done impeccably. Plus, the social content @theprimadonald, @jennyarmstrong721 and @feistyfrank churned out (and are still churning out) for @bravotv and @bravowwhl so beautifully captured the excitement of the weekend and helped everyone at home (and those of us stuck in the press room) feel like we didn’t miss a moment. 

Special thanks to @colls22 for producing our little game show, in addition to so many of the other panels on the Gold Stage. And to the talent and PR teams for masterfully coordinating travel, transportation, accommodations and very complicated appearance schedules for 185+ people — all with a smile on your faces. 

I certainly don’t know everything that went into this, so I’m sure I’m missing a lot of key elements here. But on behalf of those of us walking into BravoCon, I say “thank you.” Can’t wait to see what y’all create next year!
